John Edward: The Language Skills the World Needs
Scottish independent schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another package of excellent test results, and the added weight of this give individual and joint successes in sport, art, music and other activities in the community.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further education and higher education, the career they want to pursue and make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement this school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a favorite and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, it goes to his heart."
This statement is a powerful reminder that we cannot use only English if we want to build trust and relationships with people from other countries.
The latest results from this year's final exams show that the highest scores in the languages were achieved by students of independent schools.
A total of 68% of the students who taught foreign languages received excellent grades.
The data collected in 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of students received excellent scores for the Mandarin language, while 72% of students learning German, 69% of students learning French and 63% of students learning Spanish also received the highest scores.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key skill that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Today, languages as elective subjects are considered as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools, as in other places.
A survey conducted by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that 17 % of employers are unable to fill their jobs due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more an imperative to prepare young people for careers.
As more and more jobs require knowledge of languages, skills are key in the globalized world.
Regardless of the choice of career, people who have learned to speak a foreign language in the future will feel the benefits of such long-term skills.
A person who speaks multiple languages can communicate directly with strangers, which gives them an advantage over competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey involving more than 4,000 adults, 75% of respondents in the United Kingdom do not know a foreign language well enough to communicate on it, and French is the only language that speaks a two-digit percentage of respondents, namely 15%.
Therefore, investing in language learning is very important for today’s children.
If children learn more languages, especially the languages of developing countries, they will have more opportunities to find a good job.
In Scotland, every school offers different languages.
Some schools will include classical, modern languages in their program, while others will choose the languages that are considered to be the most important in the UK in 2020, for example Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests, independent schools will always have a diverse selection, as well as teaching staff who are expert in the field.
Scottish independent schools allow children an environment in which they will learn to prepare and equip themselves with the skills necessary for success, regardless of what the future holds for us.
One cannot ignore the fact that, in today's global business, knowledge of language is very important for the future of each country, so it must also be reflected in education.
Thus, knowledge of modern languages should indeed be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer a choice of language, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Council of Scottish Independent Schools.
