Although Ri reiterated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "progressive" approach to denuclearization in which North Korea would gradually lift sanctions, his statement is significant because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first meeting in the history of the current U.S. president and leader of North Korea in Singapore on June 12, when Kim promised to work on "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula," while Trump was confident.
North Korea wants to officially end the Korean War that lasted from 1950 to 1953, but the United States has conditioned Pyongyang to give up nuclear weapons before that.
Washington has also ignored calls for a reduction in strict international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists that denuclearization be carried out earlier and increases pressure by sanctions to forcibly achieve its goal, and even oppose the 'proclamation of the end of the war'," Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can put us on our knees is just a delusion of people who don’t know anything about us.
The main problem is that the continuation of sanctions increases distrust."
Ri did not mention whether there were plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the US president spoke about earlier this week in the United Nations.
But the minister said Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in had held as many as three meetings over the past five months and added: "If South Korea had sought denuclearization, not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come as far as this."
Despite everything, the tone of the speech of Minister Rija was vastly different from that of last year when he spoke in front of the UN General Assembly and stated that targeting the continental United States of America missiles was inevitable after the evil President Trump called Kim "a man-made missile."
