Students at Harvard attend a course where they learn how to rest well.
A new course at Harvard University has enabled all students to get a good night's sleep in an attempt to combat an increasingly widespread culture of learning with caffeine and sleepless nights.
The academic found that students at the world's best university often have no idea about the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep science at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, devised a course he considers to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He came up with the idea of a course after he gave a talk about the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
At the end of the lecture, a girl came to me and said, "Why did I just find out about this at the last year of college?"
She said no one told her how important the dream was, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, which is held for the first time this year, explains to students how good sleep habits help in academic and sports success and generally improve health.
Professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Executive Director of the University's Health Service Paul Barreira said the University decided to introduce the course after students were noticed with a serious lack of sleep during the week.
A one-on-one course consists of a series of interactive tasks.
One of these tasks includes a picture of a student dorm where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to find out what the effects of caffeine and light are, how a lack of sleep affects success, and how important a sleep routine is.
During the lecture, students learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons is then displayed that encourages students to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we think they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know how cigarettes affect health,” added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride for full-time learning before exams still exists, says the professor, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students prove that lack of sleep is an ever-increasing problem.
The professor says that the secret weapon of students against stress, exhaustion and anxiety should be a good and quality sleep. Sleeping also helps in the fight against obesity because lack of sleep affects the brain, puts it into a state of starvation and causes constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemistry and biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler devise a course after attending his lectures at Harvard's first year.
He says the course opened his eyes and inspired him to extend the course to the entire campus.
As a next step, it plans to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar subject before joining a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends students to turn on the alarm during sleep, as well as during waking up. They must be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" that emit screens of electronic devices, as well as LED lights that can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause sleep problems.
