Almanah: The Invention of the Geiger Numeral
And now follows the page from our Almanac in the show "Sunday Morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago and a few days...the birthday of the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger in Germany.
Geiger developed a method of detecting and measuring radioactivity, and from this invention a device known as the Geiger counter was later developed.
The mainstay of science since that time, Geiger's numerator has also become the mainstay of pop culture, for example in the 1950 film "Bells of Colorado" in which the main roles were played by seemingly incredible scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What is it, for God's sake?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, and it's used to detect radioactive minerals, like uranium.
